 and suicide. After the bill passed, a great many Canadians continued to challenge how sexual behaviour was governed, demanding much more exhaustive changes to the law. Fifty years later, the origins and legacies of the bill are equivocal and the state still seems interested in the bedrooms of the nation. This incisive study explains why that matters.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAbortionxLaw and legislationzCanada. 0aBirth controlxLaw and legislationzCanada. 0aHomosexualityxLaw and legislationzCanada. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh1 aAckerman, Katrina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChambers, Lori, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouville, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDummitt, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDummitt, Christopher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGroot, Scott De, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaynes, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHewitt, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHooper, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnstone, Rachael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKinsman, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPearlston, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerreault, Isabelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSethna, Christabelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSethna, Christabelle, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary